<subSubSection id="C32F6571E62BFFAC00E7FE9216C2FE04" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8A36FAE62BFFAC00E7FE9216C2FE04" blockId="5.[151,1437,152,611]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="B941EAE8E62BFFAC00E7FE921405FE5C" bold="true" box="[199,334,369,395]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D79E62BFFAC026AFE9117EBFE5C" authorityName="Riccardi" authorityYear="2020" box="[586,672,370,395]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Chaethippus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis id="B941EAE8E62BFFAC026AFE9117EBFE5C" box="[586,672,370,395]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” is derived from a Portuguese noun meaning “an inhabitant of 
<collectingRegion id="49F1F818E62BFFAC0554FE921441FE78" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
city”. The noun carioca is also used for residents of the state of 
<collectingRegion id="49F1F818E62BFFAC03F7FE761132FE78" box="[983,1145,405,431]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
and the specific epithet is referring to the Brazilian state where the specimens were collected.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32F6571E62BFFAC00E7FE3E1437FDB4" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8A36FAE62BFFAC00E7FE3E1437FDB4" blockId="5.[151,1437,152,611]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">
<emphasis id="B941EAE8E62BFFAC00E7FE3E1470FE20" bold="true" box="[199,315,477,503]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">Remarks.</emphasis>
Unfortunately, more than 
<specimenCount id="9D33FD73E62BFFAC0244FE3E1641FE20" box="[612,778,477,503]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" type="generic">100 specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C354D79E62BFFAC030FFE3E16EDFE20" authorityName="Riccardi" authorityYear="2020" box="[815,934,477,503]" class="Insecta" family="Chloropidae" genus="Chaethippus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carioca">
<emphasis id="B941EAE8E62BFFAC030FFE3E16EDFE20" box="[815,934,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">C. carioca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with the same data as the 
<typeStatus id="548E8858E62BFFAC04EDFE3E1064FE20" box="[1229,1327,477,503]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">holotype</typeStatus>
were lost in the MNRJ fire (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA44B0BE62BFFAC0146FDE214B2FDCC" author="Duarte, L. F. D." box="[358,505,513,539]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134" pagination="359 - 384" refId="ref6779" refString="Duarte, L. F. D. (2019) O Museu Nacional: ciencia e educacao numa historia institucional brasileira. Horizontes Antropologicos, 25 (53), 359 - 384. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / s 0104 - 71832019000100013" type="journal article" year="2019">Duarte 2019</bibRefCitation>
). The three 
<typeStatus id="548E8858E62BFFAC025DFDE217A3FDCC" box="[637,744,513,539]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">paratypes</typeStatus>
used for obtaining the MEV micrographs have the same data as the 
<typeStatus id="548E8858E62BFFAC00FFFDC6140FFDE8" box="[223,324,549,575]" pageId="5" pageNumber="134">holotype</typeStatus>
, however, they have another preparation set—the specimens were coated with gold and some body parts were removed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
